I came across these instructions for a DIY HD antenna made from cardboard. https://hubpages.com/art/make-this-powerful-hdtv-antenna-out-of-cardboard
I wanted to try it out but didn't like the idea of cardboard. The original version that I printed was using wood PLA, with individual supports for the bow ties. It still wasn't strong enough for my liking, but I had to see if it worked. Using regular tin foil and Elmer's wood glue, I had no problem getting the foil to adhere to the bowties. Note: Aluminum foil tape may be a better option.
I stuck with cardboard for the back reflector.
5 minute epoxy was used to glue the bowtie halves together (don't forget to print each side twice!) and sheet metal screws were used to mount the bowties to the supports and the supports to the back reflector.
After hooking it up, I was able to get 16 channels in a low altitude wooded area 50-60 miles away from major cities, which was better than nothing.
I ended up beefing up the bowties a little and combined the two supports into one to maintain the distance between sides and prevent them from moving when attached to the reflector. If anyone tries this, let me know how you make out!

This is my version 2 of a Talisman Character Organizer.
If you play Talisman, you know that keeping up with all the cards and keeping them organized can be challenging. I designed this to help keep everything visible and organized.

This helps by:

  1. Keeping alignment card clearly displayed at all times.
  2. Separating Objects from Trinkets.
  3. Limiting each character to 4 objects. (I have seperate holders for Mules and other object carriers to keep up with what objects are on which holders beyond the base carry limit)
  4. Places for up to 8 Trinkets.
  5. Up to 6 Followers and they are staggered to keep all visible.
  6. Recessed token holders for Strength, Craft and Life.
  7. Treasure Chest for Gold.
  8. Fate holders that allow you to keep up with Dark Fate vs Light Fate when playing Woodlands expansion.
  9. Modifiers section with token holders to keep up with modifiers and bonuses from Items, Trinkets, Stones and Followers.
  10. Place for Trophies and Spells.

I borrowed ideas and design elements from many places to put this together including previous designs by Talismods, Deniax and LV4626. I am always open to suggestions for improvement.

Edit 1/21/2017:
After play testing the new Organizer, I have uploaded a new revision with the following changes:

  1. Added shapes to help support the cones and an outer perimeter for cones.
  2. Split the modifiers section up to Permanent Modifiers (Such as Craft and Strength bonuses from Followers and Objects that are alway in effect) and Modifiers from Weapons (Only in effect during Battle and Psychic Combat).

Both versions still available.

Comments and suggestions are welcome and appreciated.

It was developed in the 1970s by the McDonnell Douglas company. It was developed from the Northrop YF-17 prototype for the Navy and Marine Corps of the United States. The Hornet has also been exported to seven countries to serve in its air forces. Since 1986 it has been used for aerial acrobatics by the Blue Angels air demonstration group of the US Navy.

This fighter plane combines hunting and attack capabilities to attack both aerial and ground targets. It can be seen in its designation F / A, "F" in Fighter and "A" in Attack (in Spanish: "caza" and "ataque"). The main missions it can perform are: escort, air defense, enemy air defenses, interdiction, air support and reconnaissance. Due to its versatility and reliability it has proven to be a valuable device. Although he had been criticized for his lack of scope and capacity for weapons.

The F / A-18 has been manufactured in four main versions: first the F / A-18A / B and later the improved F / A-18C / D. The A / C versions are single-seaters, while the B / D versions are two-seater. The C / D versions of the Hornet have served as the design baseline for the creation of the F / A-18E / F Super Hornet, a larger and more advanced evolution. Compared to the original Hornet, the Super Hornet is bigger, heavier, with more range and has more capacity for weaponry. The introduction of the F / A-18E / F has allowed the removal of several types of outdated aircraft (such as hunting, attack and tanker) in the US Navy, which now has the F / A-18 Hornet and Super Hornet in its fleet and, thanks to its versatility, fulfill all the missions of the retired models.

title: Hypercube evolution dual z single motor

description.text:
I made dual z lead screw mount driven by single stepper motor. Unfortunately it is not universal for all frame sizes. But using only a browser and basic cad skills you can easily adjust it. I use this setup and it is working perfectly. Only 3030 extrusion size is supported. If there is no space on the bottom you can mount motor upside down.

Important! Before printing you should probably adjust the design due to different belt length and belt angles.

There are the steps to adjust:

1) Register at https://cad.onshape.com, it is free. It is online CAD and it is very easy to use.
2) Open link to my design: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/974f7f88fbbf998db3eea4b8/w/1d0f2214bce015646147406e/e/1b0fae8ecad58d3a94cf6749
3) Click on hamburger and select copy workspace. This creates your own copy of design and you will be able to edit.
3) Go to 'reference' tab and select (double click) the sketch 'reference' in features list.
4) Here you can edit dimensions of your printer (x extrusion length and y extrusion length). Also check distance from extrusion to z axis lead screws and lead screws y position.
5) Go to dual z mount tab. Select 'belt length measue' sketch. Make sure the sketch is fully visible. Drag select everything and you will get required belt length in the right bottom corner of the screen.

Note! The length of the belt can be adjusted about -+1cm by moving stepper motor.

If you can not find belt required try to modify 'reference' sketch again or the design itself. Basic knowledge of cad software may be required.
6) Check all the tabs and all the parts in Parts section. Right click on each part and click export. Export all of them to .stl and print.

BOM
[ ] GT2 Belt (For my 400mmx400mm x and y extrusion the length is 1140mm)
[ ] 2x 36T GT2 pulley 8mm bore toothed
[ ] 2x 20T GT2 idler toothed
[ ] 1x 20T GT2 idler not toothed
[ ] 1x NEMA17 stepper motor
[ ] 6x 608 bearings (to support z axis, may be 4x will be enough)
[ ] 13x m5x10mm (for mounting)
[ ] 13x m5 hammer nuts
[ ] 4x m3x25 screws (They are shafts for idlers)
[ ] 4x m3 nuts
[ ] 4x m3x15mm screws for nema17 mount
[ ] 2x lead screws

description.text:
a small 2x 18650 powerbank enclosure.

small, compact and very simple to print and build but also very handy to have when out and about.

the board I used:
https://www.banggood.com/3Pcs-Dual-USB-5V-1A-2_1A-Mobile-Power-Bank-18650-Battery-Charger-PCB-Module-Board-p-1133268.html?rmmds=myorder&cur_warehouse=CN

the batteries I salvaged from an old laptop battery pack (saved just chucking it out)

all you'll need hardware wise are 6x M2x10mm screws/bolts to slap it all together, doesnt require any gluing etc, the whole thing is so compact there's no room for anything to rattle about inside.

the indented button one end can be held to turn the bank on and off (though the board auto powers when somethings plugged into the usb ports anyway) or double clicked to turn the led torch on at the other end.

the display obviously shows voltage percentage in the batteries but also displays power in and out aswell as voltage/ampage out.

to build:

solder a couple of wires to your board before trying to fit it into the enclosure.

join the two 18650's together, live to live, negative to negative (parallel configuration), they often come out of laptop battery packs already paired together in that way anyway

slot the button into the main body with the slightly tapered edge toward the front of the enclosure.

now insert the power board, to hold it somewhere like its final placement it helps to plug in a couple of usb cables through the enclosure which keeps the board somewhere like.

slot in the paired batteries in below the board (make sure you have them the right way round for connecting to the board, get it wrong and the board will die instantly) and let the board naturally settle back onto them.

now simply trim back the wires either end and solder them to the joints on the batteries.

bolt the end caps on and your done.

added 4x 18650 version, (10x m2x10mm screws bolts required)

title: Harbor Freight Cordless Drill Motor and BB Gearbox Conversion

description.text:
This project came as the result of wanting to have a ball bearing supported output shaft on my robot project for the this year. I originally employed a Harbor Freight cordless drills for drives on both sides of my 12 lb bot, as well as the weapon lift. You can use the stock gearbox housing, but it is only bushing supported, and would therefore require periodic greasing to keep things lubed and cool. The bottom line is that the HF gearbox is not designed for side loads that the driveline will impute to it.

So here it is; mountable from three different sides with M5 fasteners. The gearbox is held together with four M5 x 35mm long flat socket head screws. It is clearance at the joint to accept a 1.5" ID x 1.75" OD O-ring, helping to keep the grease inside the gearbox. I got them from the local hardware store for $0.65 ea. The motor attaches to the gearbox cover with the same fasteners as it was attached with the original gearbox. The original snap ring and one of the thrust washers completes the assembly with minimal endplay. The bearings are 28mm OD x 12mm ID x 8mm high shielded, and I got them through Fastenal for $1.49 each. Two required per gearbox.

Total cost for the conversion not including shipping is;
Fasteners $0.92
O-ring $0.65
Bearings $2.98
PLA Filament $1.16
Total of $5.71

O-ring spec https://www.grainger.com/product/GRAINGER-APPROVED-Round-222-Medium-Hard-Neoprene-1BUX9

description.text:
This is my version of bowden extruder using planetary gears. Main features:

  • Compact size
  • Gearbox and extruder can be used separately in your projects. Mounting holes distance is standard 41mm.
  • Spring tension is adjustable
  • The sun tooth count is 11, ring count is 31, thus gear ratio is 11/(11+31) = 11/42, roughly 1:4
  • Easy to modify. Source is availabe on onshape: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/5ee1ffe43ef2e566c07a035e/w/0bd35da36c26bcc4ebda51c2/e/f4cf60065a9aced32ceed3a0
    Onshape is browser only online cad tool. You can easily modify it to use bearings and other parts you have.

Notes

  • The sun gear is push fit on the motor shaft. You may need to file the bore a bit.
  • Mount bracket is weak, you can use any mount for nema17

BOM

  • nema17 stepper motor
  • 685 bearing (mounted in the cover part to support shaft)
  • 625 bearing (idler)
  • 623 bearing or 623 groove bearing (no groove is required, i just had them) Use appropriate rotor file.
  • 9mm-10mm shaft (for idler bearing, i cut a piece of 5mm nail)
  • mk7 drive gear
  • 3x m3x30mm screws (extruder mount)
  • m3x12mm screw (extruder mount)
  • 3x m3x20mm screw, button head is required, head height should be lower that 2mm (planet gears shafts)
  • 4x m3x12mm (to mount nema17)
  • 7x m3 nuts
  • m5x30mm bolt with hex head (to fit into rotor)
  • m5x15mm screw with button head (to adjust spring tension)
  • optional: 2x m5x10mm screws with hammer nuts (to mount on 2020 or 3030 frames)
  • m5 nut
  • 20x7x5mm spring

Same helmet for Luke and Leia, as well as some Rogue One Rebel Troopers (with a different decals however), and Battlefront desert trooper.

Enjoy and please show us the ones you make !

IMPORTANT !!! Note regarding the size !!!!
This helmet is sized for a 58-62cm perimeter head (at hear level) (roughly 16cm*20cm).
If you are ~54cm perimeter, you should print at 93% size. And even lower/bigger size if your head is smaller/bigger.

Multiple versions available :

  • Full or 4parts. To print at once or in 4 parts (fit a 151515cm printer).
  • With or Without decals. In the movie some Endor trooper have the decals but not all. Leia and Luke have it. This "decals" is meant to disappear almost completely when doing the surface finishing, but still here to help paint it.
  • 3 possibles "back part". There has been debate if it's indented or not the stripes in the back of the helmet, and the shape. The Costumes book about Original Trilogy clearly show it's just paint and squared corners. However, I put indented version and squared or rounded corners for people preferring that.

Please check instructions on the pictures for assembly order of the 4 parts version.
In full or 4 parts case you will still have to trim the "brims" to fit to your head.
See above my Make in the pictures. Printed in ABS, assembled and glued with abs-acetone paste, sanded, acetone smooth and sanded again. Primed, and painted with airbrush and "mustard technique" for the paint chips.
Please note that the model is free of any bumps in it, but using hot air fun (be careful!), and a tool to push the plastic, you can add some if desired. See examples in my Make.

I extended the rail from 80mm to 100mm length, for stability and lowering the centre of gravity. Because the extra distance between ball bearings, the spool goes a bit deeper into the channel of the holder. That is why i cut out a circular shape from the walls, so a full spool of filament won't touch the holder and rub against it.

Please let me know if you have any troubles with it, so i can get you sorted out with an improved model. Maybe use a different cutout radius.

Also, because of the distance between walls, i made some M8 washers to center the ball-bearing in the holder channel. It makes a lot of difference even with the original design. I am using 8 pieces per screw. Two outside and two on the inside, on each side of the ball bearing. That way it is centred, and the edge of the spool cannot jam in-between the wall and the bearing. See the photos.

I'm using M8x30mm screws, that's why they are a bit longer.

description.text:
This is a mounting bracket for the 2-channel version of those super common electro-magnetic relays that are so nicely controllable by microcontrollers like Arduino etc. In fact this bracket offers an optional side-car for an Arduino Nano. The Nano is mounted into the sidecar with hot glue, then the sidecar is screwed to the main bracket with #2 x 1/4" sheetmetal screws. The main bracket also uses #2 x 1/4" screws to attach the relay board.

As usual, screw slots (sized for #6 sheetmetal screws) are spaced at 0.5cm multiples, for convenient mounting on Bud Industries back panels.

We use this combo as a sleep/power controller, in conjunction with the super awesome Arduino low-power sleep library, to control a CDMA modem and various sensor electronics, all running on solar power. Every x minutes, the Arduino wakes up and Relay 1 applies power to the modem for about 45 seconds so it can "warm up" (find connection), then Relay 2 powers up the rest of the electronics, long enough to take readings and upload them to our cloud servers at http://tools.valarm.net - cool, right?

Yeah, we could have ditched the whole relay board with a couple of SSRs or even transistors. But these things are SUPER CHEAP, you know? Also very reliable, can handle a ton of power, and are ready to rock out of the box.

First converted the Stl from original files to Stp in Freecad.
Then modified the part in Inventor.

Extruder From one of the Things in Remixed From section (or alike), without the idler obviously.
1# M3x10
2# M3x16
Sand Paper (Grade < 300)
CA Glue
608 Bearing
OptoEndstop or a Transmissive Optical Sensor

1. First you have to create a rough surface on idler bearing outer surface .
    Simply slide it several times on the sand paper until it’s not shinny and slippery anymore.

  2. Hold the encoder disk and bearing together, I suggest to use the shielded type of the bearing with metal covers on both side (608ZZ).
    Add 4 drops of CA glue around the encoder disk base and try to spread it with a piece of wire or something and let it dry or use the CA glue accelerator.

  3. Place the Bearing and the encoder wheel on the idler.

  4. Place the optoendstop and hold it in place with a M3x10 bolt.

  5. Join the Idler and extruder body with a M3x16 bolt. Don’t tight them too much though.

  6. Push the filament in and tighten the adjustment screw to push it to the extruder gear.

  7. Connect the signal wire to one of free pins of ramps, I Suggest the X,Y or Z max Endstop.

First tighten the adjustment screw and the check if you can rotate the idler bearing with hand, if you can, the bearing surface is not rough enough and it slips and you have to scratch it more with sand paper.

Upload your configuration.h to the Repetier online configurator and go to the Mechanics tab.
https://www.repetier.com/firmware/v100/index.php

At the bottom of the page there is Jam detection, set the jam detection method to Steps between signal changes don’t touch anything else for now, we have to do it one more time.
(In case you are using the exact same setup(My extruder Step/mm is 283), you will end up with the value of around 1710 for Regular steps for a cycle. I suggest that you set Slowdown steps to 3000, Slowdown to 60%, Steps for jam detection 5000, Min. steps for signal change to 20)

Head over to Tools tab and at the bottom of the page there is Jam detection pin, choose the pin you already connected the signal wire of you optoendstop.
Uncheck Enable Pull Up Resistor.
Install the new firmware.

Make sure your filament is out of the hotend.
Connect your 3D Printer via USB, Open Repetier host, now we are going to debug the jam detection system.

First you have to put M302 to allow cold extrusions.

Then enter M602 S1 to activate debug mode for jam system.

Open Printer Setting in upper right corner of Repetier host
And set the Manual Extrusion Speed to 0.5 and 10 and Manual Retraction Speed to 80, click OK.

Now press the extruder buttons, extrude 100mm slow, then fast, and the retract 100mm two times.

See the log section, you will see lots of Jam Signal Steps logs
If they are around 100% +-3%, then you are good to go.

If they had some other values, take an average from the steps, and put the value in the Regular steps for a cycle in online configurator.

And put 140% of the New Jam Steps value to the slowdown steps and 230% of it to the Jam Error Steps.

It has to be done at this stage, you can repeat the process in case of false errors.

If you have any questions, please ask =)

A first pass at making some terrain to go with the Kallistra wargaming tiles that I have. I cannot endorse their hex tiles enough. They're my favorite wargaming terrain product:

https://www.kallistra.co.uk/

The hex terrain is 100mm from flat edge to flat edge. I plan to make river/road hexes, slopes, and any other single-hex terrain that takes my fancy. Feel free to make requests.

I will add additional slope hexagons to this collection (for 1, 2, and 3 "high sides" slopes). The first set of slopes will mate to a single hex tile height. I may later make slopes to match up with higher tile stacks, if there's demand.

I will also add various river/road curves, junctions, and end caps. May also make some single-hex hills, ponds, marshes, etc.

Tip me with Bitcoin at the address below:
14U3VBvFWYwz5A6Rtox2PiWDfZFLFJpFtZ

Making the Slopes

The only software program I used was Blender, which is free. I started by making a basic hexagon tile template. I created a "cylinder," but I limited it's number of sides to 6, creating a regular hexagon. I adjusted its dimensions so that the hexagon would be 100mm (~ 4 inches, "units" in Blender terms) from flat edge to flat edge, and 3mm high.

I then did some planning, thinking about how hill/slope tiles would need to tessellate (interconnect together). Each slope hex would need a certain number of "high" sides and a certain number of "low" sides. I thought of every possible combination and orientation and listed them out on paper. These ranged from "0," where all of the hex sides are low, but the middle is high, to "6," where all sides are high, and therefore the tile is just a thicker hexagon. For tiles with 2 through 4 high sides, there are multiple different possible configurations. For example, if 2 sides are high, the two high sides could be directly adjacent, could have one hex side between them, or could be directly opposite one another (3 different configurations). I made a design for each of these configurations.

One of the "gotchas" of the process was figuring out that I needed to determine whether each vertex (i.e. corner) of the hexagon was "high" or "low," and whether the midpoint of each hex side should be high or low. I kept the number of vertices describing the tile to the absolute minimum at this point. This point is complex and a little tough to explain in writing.

To give each hex a plateau effect, so that there would be a flatter area in the center of each slope, I described a smaller hexagon shape of points in the center of each hex tile. The vertices of this central hex were each halfway between the center point and the vertices at the outside of the hex tile. For each tile, I made this central, smaller hexagonal region "high." I then went around the edge of the tile, and depending on which slope configuration I was creating, I raised the vertices along the top of the outside edge of the hex (at each "point" of the hexagon, and at the center of each hex side). See the screenshot I've attached for an example of what one of these basic tiles would look like. The basic design of the hex tile is important, and I would need to includes some drawings or screenshots of the file in-progress to really explain it well.

After creating and saving each of the basic slope shapes, the next step was to "rough-up" the surface of each tile. I used the Subdivide tool in Blender to make the top surface of each hex tile more complicated (i.e. give the top surface many more faces to work with). Then I used Blender's sculpting tool to randomly draw all over the top surface of the tile. This had an effect similar to slathering sculpting putty all over the surface. Then I used the flatten sculpting brush to smooth out the random mess I'd made, making the slope look organic. I particularly focused on sculpting over and smoothing out the hard line edges.

Another "gotcha" I encountered was caused by this sculpting step. My sculpting process ended up affecting the bottom surface of each tile, causing the bottom to no longer be totally flat. This caused an issue with printing, as the bottom surface of each tile wasn't flush with the print bed. The result was that the corners of the tiles tended to "peel upwards" when printing. I discovered this issue and manually reset the bottoms of each tile to be totally flat.

description.text: Fairly simple way to save time rolling coins. Just fill up the applicable holder with the correct denomination of coin; any amount in excess of the correct amount should slide off the top if tilted. The design of this was rather simple, really. I found the measurements of each of the individual coins, both diameter and thickness, and designed the tubes accordingly. Each individual tube is designed to hold the exact amount of coins necessary to roll:

Quarter - 40
Dime - 50
Nickel - 40
Penny - 50

Any coin over the amount should slide off the top if tilted to one side or the other. The tray was built just for convenience, and isn't necessary. Once full, you should be able to shimmy an empty coin roll around the side of the tube-stacked coins, making it easy to roll.

description.text:
Designers were Chris Dupuis, Michael Gray, Gary Gygax, Larry Kessling, David R. Megarry, S. Schwab and Steve Winter
In many ways Dungeon! is similar to Dungeons & Dragons, although much simplified and transformed into a board game. Players explore a dungeon that is divided into levels of increasing difficulty, fighting monsters for valuable treasure. As players venture deeper into the dungeon, the monsters become more difficult and the treasure more valuable. Several character classes each have slightly different fighting abilities – most notably the wizard, who can cast spells. Combat is simulated using dice; players roll the dice to attack a monster, and if unsuccessful, the dice are rolled to determine the effect of the monster's counter-attack.
The winner is the first player to bring a certain amount of treasure back to the Dungeon's entrance.

title: WLToys 24438 ECX Temper 1/24 Crawler Articulation Fix

description.text:
I designed these parts to fix the axle shift during articulation for the WLToys 24438 1/24th scale crawler. This fix reverses the triangulation of the lower links by replacing the lower transmission mount and swapping locations of different length ball ends.

Instructions:

  1. Print 1 of the Trans Mount parts and 4 of the Tiny Washers.
  2. Remove the long ball ends from lower shock mount and the short ball ends from the lower axle mount. Install 1 Tiny Washer on each long ball ends and screw them into the lower axle mount in the same orientation as original short ball ends.
  3. Install the short ball ends from lower axle mount into the newly printed Trans Mount, facing inwards instead of out. This step is a little difficult. I used a long ball end to thread the holes in the Trans Mount from the outside then installed the short ball ends in the holes.
  4. Finally, move medium ball ends from the old transmission mount to lower shock mount position and reassemble everything.

So I bought a "complete" G1 jetfire off of ebay only to find that the left shoulder had been glued in place and was missing the spring, the gear and the screw. Tomorrow I'll go for the spring and screw at a hardware store, but this gear turned out nicely. You might need to shave off the inside ever so slightly to get it to smoothly go on the toy's post, and you might need to sand/file down the exterior slightly to get the gear to fit in the should slot.

The gear works great. You will have a much harder time finding a screw and spring if those are lost. I went to a local ace hardware, but it was very difficult to find an exact match. I ended up getting a screw that had a much tighter threading and drilling the hole out a bit to fit the new screw. The washer was barely large enough to attach. If anyone has a suggestion of where to get small screws and springs for toys, I'm all ears.

I printed at 0.3mm, but I imagine 0.1mm would be better for a part like this, since I can imagine the grinding eventually rubbing the gear smooth.

Overall the project was a success and instead of a glued in place left arm, I now have a jetfire that is fully transformable again.

description.text:
I wanted to get a real sound voltex controller but didn't have the money at the moment. So I stripped an old fight stick I made and modeled a controller enclosure for 8 - 30mm screwbuttons and 2 - 24mm short stem screwbuttons. The PCB I used to base the design from was an akishop ps360+.

Instructions:
Print the top panel first and install your buttons.
Print bottom panel and mount your pcb (hole cutout in the side is sized for an akishop ps360+)
Print left and right walls
Run wiring from your pcb to the buttons in your top panel
Connect left and right walls to the bottom panel
Slot in the hinge pins for the top panel starting first with one side, and then flexing the opposite side wall slightly to all the other pin to slide into place.
The back wall is optional but helps with rigidity for consistent button presses, this would be the point where print and connect it if you wish to use it. The cutouts at the top are intended for external cable management if you want to keep your wiring long like I did instead of cutting it to fit.

Build Notes:
Attaching rubber feet to the bottom panel helps keep the controller in place much more easily when playing.
Cutouts at the top of the back panel are for routing your pcb wiring out of the case if you don't cut it to fit inside (I had a ton of excess and didnt wanna recrimp things).

description.text:
The main idea behind this plate is to allow me flexibility in what tool I put on the x-carriage, where I put fans and other sensors etc. I'm planning to create a few parts which are based on this plate.

At present I'm just printing this plate twice and using for both sides. Technically over-kill but you never know ( quad extruder anyone? )

To use this plate you will need heat-set inserts. Either from Lulzbot or McMaster. I have set the spacing to be 20mm center to center and they should be just the right size to take these inserts. The lulzbot guys did a nice write-up demonstrating how to put them in.

You will also need the following:

  1. 4 x mini-v wheel kits ( either delrin or polycarb )
  2. 4 x 6mm spacers
  3. 4 x 6mm eccentric spacers
  4. 4 x M5 45mm
  5. 4 nylock nuts ( or regular and thread lock )
  6. For each plate, 26 heat-set inserts ( see above for link options )

I'm still messing around with the extruder mounts. The titan large diameter gear screws around with the spacing so it sticks out kinda far which could make the hotend subject to moving during rapid transitions.

Also note, this is a work in progress. I've assembled it and done movement tests but have not used it for anything serious. Any thoughts or ideas on improvements or changes would be welcome. I plan to make a laser engraver mount and going to try a cnc mill later.

The c-bot you see in the photos is a small form factor so I can iterate on this kind of stuff without taking my main printer down so the plate looks huge ;)

description.text:
Tritium is radioactive hydrogen - it's also called H^3. It's a byproduct of reactors and when you put it into a tube lined with phosporus it gives off a glow that's a bit dimmer than a fluorescent glow stick, except that it stays lit for decades. You can buy tritium vials on etsy and Ebay and Alibaba. In the US they can be hard to find because selling them requires a license from the Nuclear Regulatory Commission but they are used in fancy watches and on gun sights and as far as I'm aware they aren't illegal. In other countries, like the UK among many others, they are not too hard to buy. Check with your local laws before buying one. They usually sell for less than USD$20.

This thing is a 3D printed tritium vial holder that protects the glass and also - I think - looks pretty cool. There are lots of vial holders out there for 3x22.5mm vial sizes but this one is for the larger 25mm x 3.5mm vials which are larger and emit a bit more light. It's coded in OpenSCAD so if you want to resize it, you can.

I printed in <10 minutes on my Printrbot Simple Metal on 0.2mm layer height without support. Print one of each .stl.

One question that lots of people - like my wife - ask me is "if it's radioactive, is it safe" and the answer is "yes, it's totally safe." Tritium emits beta particles which are electrons. I have a Geiger counter and you can see that there's no measurement when the vial is more than ~5cm away from the detector. So 5cm (2 inches) of air is enough to stop any radioactivity. If you stick a piece of paper between the vial and the detector, the paper is enough to stop it. The radioactivity from tritium vials is on par from old CRT monitors (which also shoot electrons at phosphorus on glass to produce a glow) These particles are too weak to penetrate human skin at all. If you ate the vial, that would likely not be good. But there are a whole lot of cleaning supplies around a house that also wouldn't be good to eat.

description.text:
This is a customization and fix of a few different Cafe Racers Things. I took what I liked from each, modified some, repaired some, and created some completely new pieces to suit my vision. I wanted the wheels to spin, so I made the changes needed for that to happen. I also had to fix a few things that would prevent the model from being assembled at all. I also wanted a twin (all bikes should have symmetrical exhausts) so I modified the engine to have a second exhaust port and mirrored the pipe. I also HATED the big ole clunky solid triple tree (that was impossible to mount to the tank btw...) so I made up some normal plates that leave the forks exposed... as it should be in a perfect world. There are some pieces that would be too small to print with any accuracy, so I used the "sharpie paint" on a few to give them a little more detail.

The files included are the exact files I printed the Blue model with, so they work. Every part is designed to sit flat on the print bed. Minor cleaning of holes with a drill and trimming of the bottoms and this model goes together easily.

There are some options (thus a few extra pieces) that you can chose: single or dual front brakes, rear brakes or no, clipons or standard drag bars, 1 tach or tach and speedo combo... its up to you.

I printed this model at 200% to give it a little more presence, but it will print at any size your printer can handle.

Some of the bits here are only available in this thing, so, If you use them, please give credit...

title: Star Trek Bolivar class cut to print

description.text:
This is a cut and ready to print version of outcastrc's Star Trek Bolivar class 1:2000 (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2140965). I have printed the ship at 250% using cura and that puts it in near perfect scale with Polar Lights 1/1000 Enterprise refit, see the pictures for reference. No support was needed for the vertical saucer halves, I doubt the horizontal saucer halves need it either. I used primer filler for the saucer and I lost some detail but it was so fine, you would be unlikely to avoid losing it without printing at a much larger scale. It you have a CR-10 S5, you can try printing th ship at 1/350 scale, I bet that would sharpen the detail.
Be very patient when gluing the nacelle and hull onto the saucer, I used epoxy resin so I would have time to position the pieces as straight as possible. I would be careful with super glue.

Remember 250% for 1/1000 scale. The saucer should be 143mm-144mm wide.

title: Logitech Harmony IR Mini Blaster mount for LG 55UH615A TV

description.text:
My Logitech Harmony Mini IR Blaster (Logitech PN: 993-000191) was not working with my TV as the LG LG55UH615A TV has a narrow front field of view for the remote control. It is recessed in a narrow channel that is under the bezel.

After testing, it was clear that the IR light needed to come into the front of the TV and it wouldn't work being bounced off of anything far away, so I created a bracket for the IR blaster to sit just under the TV and reflect into the TV's sensor. Now the Harmony Hub works every time, without fail.

On the back, wire wrap posts lets you neatly store the excess IR blaster wire.

Assembly should easily mount to tv and hold without any tape. There is a spot to use some thin double-sided tape if needed.
